844. Backspace String Compare
Problem

Given two strings s and t containing lowercase letters and '#' (backspace), return true if they are equal after processing all backspaces.

Example
s = "ab#c"
t = "ad#c"

Output: true

After processing:

s → "ac"
t → "ac"

Approach 1: Brute Force (Stack/StringBuilder)
Intuition

Simulate typing in an editor:

Character → add it.
# → remove last character (if exists).
Compare the final processed strings.

Java Solution:
class Solution {
    private String build(String str) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();

        for (char ch : str.toCharArray()) {
            if (ch != '#') {
                sb.append(ch);
            } else if (sb.length() > 0) {
                sb.deleteCharAt(sb.length() - 1);
            }
        }

        return sb.toString();
    }

    public boolean backspaceCompare(String s, String t) {
        return build(s).equals(build(t));
    }
}

Dry Run
s = "ab#c"

| Char | Result |
| ---- | ------ |
| a    | a      |
| b    | ab     |
| #    | a      |
| c    | ac     |

Processed s = "ac"

Similarly,

t = "ad#c" → "ac"

Compare:

"ac" == "ac" → true
Complexity
Time: O(n + m)
Space: O(n + m)


Approach 2: Optimal (Two Pointers)

Intuition
Traverse both strings from right to left.

# means skip a character.
Maintain a skip count for each string.
Find the next valid character in both strings and compare them.

This avoids building new strings or using stacks.

Algorithm
Set i = s.length()-1, j = t.length()-1.
Find the next valid character in s.
Find the next valid character in t.
Compare characters:
If different → return false.
Move both pointers left.
If traversal finishes successfully → return true.

Java Solution
class Solution {
    public boolean backspaceCompare(String s, String t) {
        int i = s.length() - 1;
        int j = t.length() - 1;

        int skipS = 0, skipT = 0;

        while (i >= 0 || j >= 0) {

            while (i >= 0) {
                if (s.charAt(i) == '#') {
                    skipS++;
                    i--;
                } else if (skipS > 0) {
                    skipS--;
                    i--;
                } else {
                    break;
                }
            }

            while (j >= 0) {
                if (t.charAt(j) == '#') {
                    skipT++;
                    j--;
                } else if (skipT > 0) {
                    skipT--;
                    j--;
                } else {
                    break;
                }
            }

            if (i >= 0 && j >= 0 &&
                s.charAt(i) != t.charAt(j)) {
                return false;
            }

            if ((i >= 0) != (j >= 0)) {
                return false;
            }

            i--;
            j--;
        }

        return true;
    }
}

Dry Run
Example
s = "ab#c"
t = "ad#c"

Processed strings:

ab#c → ac
ad#c → ac

Pointer traversal:
| s ptr       | t ptr       | Valid Char S | Valid Char T |
| ----------- | ----------- | ------------ | ------------ |
| c           | c           | c            | c            |
| # removes b | # removes d | a            | a            |


All characters match.

Result = true
Complexity
Time: O(n + m)
Space: O(1)
Key Trick

Process from right to left.

'#'  -> increase skip count
char -> skip if skip count > 0

Compare only the next valid characters of both strings. This achieves O(1) extra space without using a stack.
